body:
# HCL Expressions

Expressions in Terraform compute values from references, operations, and function calls. Every argument value in HCL is an expression — from simple string literals to complex for expressions over nested structures.

## References

Expressions reference named values using dot-separated paths:

```hcl
# Resource attributes
aws_instance.web.id
aws_instance.web.public_ip
aws_instance.web.tags["Name"]

# Input variables
var.instance_type
var.environment
var.database_config.engine

# Local values
local.common_tags
local.name_prefix

# Data source attributes
data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
data.aws_vpc.main.cidr_block

# Module outputs
module.vpc.vpc_id
module.vpc.private_subnet_ids

# Special references
self.id                  # Within provisioners
each.key                 # In for_each resources
each.value               # In for_each resources
count.index              # In count resources
path.module              # Path to current module
path.root                # Path to root module
path.cwd                 # Current working directory
terraform.workspace      # Current workspace name
```

## String Interpolation and Templates

Embed expressions in strings with `${...}` syntax:

```hcl
# Basic interpolation
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  tags = {
    Name = "${var.project}-${var.environment}-web"
  }
}

# Directive templates — conditionals and loops in strings
locals {
  greeting = "Hello, ${var.name != "" ? var.name : "World"}!"
}

# Heredoc syntax for multi-line strings
resource "aws_iam_policy" "example" {
  policy = <<-EOT
    {
      "Version": "2012-10-17",
      "Statement": [{
        "Effect": "Allow",
        "Action": "s3:GetObject",
        "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::${var.bucket_name}/*"
      }]
    }
  EOT
}

# templatefile() for external templates
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  user_data = templatefile("${path.module}/user-data.sh.tpl", {
    environment = var.environment
    db_host     = aws_db_instance.main.endpoint
    app_port    = 8080
  })
}
```

Use `templatefile()` from [[terraform/hcl/functions]] for complex templates — it supports `%{ for ... }` and `%{ if ... }` directives.

## Conditional Expressions

The ternary operator selects between two values:

```hcl
# condition ? true_value : false_value
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  instance_type = var.environment == "prod" ? "t3.large" : "t3.micro"

  # Conditionally include a block
  monitoring = var.environment == "prod" ? true : false
}

# Conditional resource creation (count)
resource "aws_cloudwatch_metric_alarm" "cpu" {
  count = var.environment == "prod" ? 1 : 0

  alarm_name  = "${var.project}-high-cpu"
  metric_name = "CPUUtilization"
  threshold   = 80
}

# Conditional output
output "alarm_arn" {
  value = var.environment == "prod" ? aws_cloudwatch_metric_alarm.cpu[0].arn : null
}

# Combine with coalesce for fallbacks
locals {
  instance_type = coalesce(var.instance_type_override, var.environment == "prod" ? "t3.large" : "t3.micro")
}
```

## For Expressions

Transform collections with `for` expressions:

```hcl
# List comprehension — transform a list
locals {
  upper_names = [for name in var.names : upper(name)]
  # ["ALICE", "BOB", "CHARLIE"]
}

# Map comprehension — build a map
locals {
  instance_ids = { for inst in aws_instance.web : inst.tags["Name"] => inst.id }
  # { "web-1" = "i-abc123", "web-2" = "i-def456" }
}

# Filtering with if clause
locals {
  public_subnets = [for s in var.subnets : s.id if s.public == true]
  large_instances = { for k, v in var.instances : k => v if v.size == "large" }
}

# Nested for — flatten structure
locals {
  all_ports = flatten([
    for sg_name, sg in var.security_groups : [
      for rule in sg.ingress_rules : {
        sg_name = sg_name
        port    = rule.port
        cidr    = rule.cidr
      }
    ]
  ])
}
```

Wrap in `[ ]` for lists, `{ }` for maps. Use `=>` for key-value pairs in maps.

## Splat Expressions

Extract a single attribute from a list of objects:

```hcl
# Full splat — equivalent to [for o in list : o.attr]
output "instance_ids" {
  value = aws_instance.web[*].id
}

output "private_ips" {
  value = aws_instance.web[*].private_ip
}

# Useful with data sources
data "aws_instances" "tagged" {
  filter {
    name   = "tag:Environment"
    values = [var.environment]
  }
}

output "running_ids" {
  value = data.aws_instances.tagged.ids
}
```

`[*]` is syntactic sugar for `[for item in list : item.attr]`.

## Dynamic Blocks

Generate repeated nested blocks from collections:

```hcl
resource "aws_security_group" "web" {
  name   = "${var.project}-web-sg"
  vpc_id = var.vpc_id

  dynamic "ingress" {
    for_each = var.ingress_rules
    content {
      from_port   = ingress.value.port
      to_port     = ingress.value.port
      protocol    = ingress.value.protocol
      cidr_blocks = ingress.value.cidr_blocks
      description = ingress.value.description
    }
  }

  dynamic "egress" {
    for_each = var.egress_rules
    content {
      from_port   = egress.value.port
      to_port     = egress.value.port
      protocol    = egress.value.protocol
      cidr_blocks = egress.value.cidr_blocks
    }
  }
}

# Nested dynamic blocks
resource "aws_lb_listener" "front" {
  load_balancer_arn = aws_lb.main.arn
  port              = 443
  protocol          = "HTTPS"

  dynamic "default_action" {
    for_each = var.listener_actions
    content {
      type             = default_action.value.type
      target_group_arn = default_action.value.target_group_arn

      dynamic "redirect" {
        for_each = default_action.value.type == "redirect" ? [default_action.value.redirect] : []
        content {
          port        = redirect.value.port
          protocol    = redirect.value.protocol
          status_code = redirect.value.status_code
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Inside a `dynamic` block, the iterator defaults to the block name (e.g. `ingress.value`). Override with the `iterator` argument.

## count and for_each

Control resource multiplication:

```hcl
# count — create N identical resources
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  count = var.instance_count

  ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
  instance_type = var.instance_type
  subnet_id     = var.subnet_ids[count.index % length(var.subnet_ids)]

  tags = {
    Name = "${var.project}-web-${count.index + 1}"
  }
}

# Reference: aws_instance.web[0].id, aws_instance.web[*].id

# for_each with a map — create named resources
resource "aws_iam_user" "team" {
  for_each = tomap({
    alice = { role = "admin",     email = "alice@example.com" }
    bob   = { role = "developer", email = "bob@example.com" }
    carol = { role = "developer", email = "carol@example.com" }
  })

  name = each.key
  tags = {
    Role  = each.value.role
    Email = each.value.email
  }
}

# Reference: aws_iam_user.team["alice"].arn

# for_each with a set
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "data" {
  for_each = toset(["raw", "processed", "archive"])

  bucket = "${var.project}-${each.key}-${var.environment}"

  tags = local.common_tags
}

# Reference: aws_s3_bucket.data["raw"].arn
```

Prefer `for_each` over `count` — it uses keys instead of indices, so removing an item from the middle of a list does not force recreation of subsequent resources.

## Operators

```hcl
# Arithmetic: +, -, *, /, %
locals {
  total_storage = var.instance_count * var.storage_per_instance
}

# Comparison: ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=
# Logical: &&, ||, !
locals {
  needs_scaling = var.instance_count > 1 && var.environment == "prod"
  is_disabled   = !var.enabled
}
```
